**Narrative Log - 2026-05-05**

This was a contract-and-proof day. The work did not try to make Codexify bigger; it tried to make the existing promises more legible and harder to accidentally overstate. That kind of day tends to look quiet from the outside, but it changes the system in a more durable way than another thin feature layer would.

The first move was to refresh the morning audit artifacts. That kept the day’s status grounded in a current dated report instead of forcing anyone to infer reality from older snapshots. In a system like this, that matters because release posture and implementation posture drift apart easily if the audit trail lags behind the code.

The heavier lift was the workspace proof harness. The new harness for `retrievalSource="workspace"` does a few things in sequence: it stages a sentinel note, indexes it through the Obsidian control plane, creates a real Guardian thread, sends a prompt that should only be answerable from that note, and then waits for the actual queue-backed completion path. That sequence is important because it separates acceptance from completion and completion from retrieval evidence. The day’s real correction was to stop treating the first part of the chain as if it proved the whole chain.

That same correction shows up in the supporting docs. The ADR, the proof harness README, the current-state file, and the flow/config notes now all point at the same truth: this harness proves the supported local Compose path, and nothing broader. That kind of boundary-setting is not cosmetic. It prevents the proof artifact from being read as a claim about packaged desktop behavior, web-only access, or alternate install modes.

The desktop shell work follows the same pattern. Adding a Docker-hosted WebUI service and exposing a direct browser-open command makes that path explicit. It does not collapse the desktop app and the web bundle into one vague release story. Instead, it gives the runtime a named way to open the web surface when that surface is actually the right one to use. That is a small change structurally, but it removes a lot of confusion from how the app presents its available surfaces.

By the end of the day, the system was more truthful in two places at once. The workspace retrieval story now has a real proof harness instead of just a contract label, and the desktop shell now has an explicit way to reach the Docker-hosted WebUI. Both changes are about reducing ambiguity, which is often the real work in a late-beta system.

What this makes possible next is straightforward: run the live proof on the supported stack, confirm the runtime posture again, and then treat the workspace retrieval seam as something we have actually evidenced rather than merely described.



